To connect a Google Sheet to a PostgreSQL database as a read-only data source, you have a few excellent options depending on your technical comfort level and security requirements. Because your database is **onsite** (on-premises), the biggest hurdle will be ensuring Google’s cloud servers can securely talk to your local network.

Here are the three best ways to pull this off, ranked from easiest to most robust.

---

## Option 1: BigQuery Omni / Cloud SQL Federated Queries (Most Enterprise-Secure)

If security is a high priority and you don't want to expose your onsite database directly to the public internet, using Google Cloud as a bridge is the gold standard.

1. **The Bridge:** Set up a secure VPN or Google Cloud Interconnect from your onsite network to Google Cloud Platform (GCP).
2. **The Connection:** Use **Cloud SQL Federated Queries** or **BigQuery Connection Service** to link BigQuery to your onsite Postgres instance.
3. **The Sheet:** In Google Sheets, use the native **Data > Data connectors > Connect to BigQuery** feature.

> 💡 **Why this is great:** It is incredibly secure, handles massive datasets easily, and Google Sheets has a built-in, native UI for BigQuery that requires zero coding for the end-user.

---

## Option 2: Apps Script with JDBC (The Direct, Code-Based Route)

Google Apps Script has a built-in `Jdbc` service that can connect directly to PostgreSQL. You can write a short script that wipes the sheet and pulls fresh data whenever a button is clicked or on a time-based trigger (e.g., every hour).

### 1. Whitelist Google's IP Addresses

Because your database is onsite, your network administrator will need to open a port (usually `5432`) and whitelist Google's App Script IP address ranges so the request isn't blocked by your firewall.

### 2. The Apps Script Code

In your Google Sheet, go to **Extensions > Apps Script** and paste a script similar to this:

```javascript
function pullPostgresData() {
  var conn = Jdbc.getConnection("jdbc:postgresql://YOUR_ONSITE_IP:5432/YOUR_DB_NAME", "YOUR_READONLY_USER", "YOUR_PASSWORD");
  
  // Select your data
  var stmt = conn.createStatement();
  var results = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM your_table LIMIT 1000");
  
  var metaData = results.getMetaData();
  var numCols = metaData.getColumnCount();
  
  var sheet = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet().getActiveSheet();
  sheet.clear(); // Clear existing data
  
  // Add Headers
  var headers = [];
  for (var i = 1; i <= numCols; i++) {
    headers.push(metaData.getColumnName(i));
  }
  sheet.appendRow(headers);
  
  // Add Rows
  while (results.next()) {
    var row = [];
    for (var i = 1; i <= numCols; i++) {
      row.push(results.getString(i));
    }
    sheet.appendRow(row);
  }
  
  results.close();
  stmt.close();
  conn.close();
}

```

